A history of my changes to pre_parser.mly.

Initial commit: 1b5db33...

726 states. (Assuming --lalr mode.)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/28

Remove all uses of the [error] token.

707 states, 367 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/28

Added a phantom context parameter to [specifier_qualifier_list]. This allows
distinguishing the two uses of specifier_qualifier_list, namely within a
type_name and within a struct_declaration. This provides more "static context"
and allows giving a better syntax error message.

716 states, 374 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/28

Instead of inline options everywhere, use them only where necessary to avoid a
conflict. The number of states goes down from 716 to 609, and the number of
error messages that must be invented goes down as well.

609 states, 305 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/30

In direct_abstract_declarator, changed option(assignment_expression) to
ioption(assignment_expression), as follows:

  direct_abstract_declarator:
  | ioption(direct_abstract_declarator) LBRACK type_qualifier_list? ioption(assignment_expression) RBRACK

This allows us to give distinct error messages for the case where an
expression has been read and the case where an expression has not
been read. In other words, more "static context".

Analogous change in direct_declarator.

611 states, 305 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/30

Created an inline clone of abstract_declarator, called
inline_abstract_declarator.

In direct_abstract_declarator, changed abstract_declarator to
inline_abstract_declarator, as follows:

  direct_abstract_declarator:
  | LPAREN inline_abstract_declarator RPAREN

616 states, 308 error states.

Before this change, there was an error state that seemed quite difficult to
explain, again by lack of static context. Here are my notes:

  translation_unit_file: ALIGNAS LPAREN VOID LPAREN LPAREN RPAREN COMMA 
  ##
  ## Ends in an error in state: 294.
  ##
  ## direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN abstract_declarator . RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK COMMA ]
  ##
  ## WARNING: This example involves spurious reductions.
  ## This implies that, although the LR(1) items shown above provide an
  ## accurate view of the past (what has been recognized so far), they
  ## may provide an INCOMPLETE view of the future (what was expected next).
  ## In state 291, spurious reduction of production abstract_declarator -> direct_abstract_declarator 
  ##

  # The first LPAREN in this example must be the beginning of an abstract_declarator.
  # It leads us into a state where we do not yet know the meaning of the opening parenthesis:
  #   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . abstract_declarator RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
  #   direct_abstract_declarator -> LPAREN . in_context(option(parameter_type_list)) RPAREN [ RPAREN LPAREN LBRACK ]
  # i.e. (a) this could be the opening parenthesis in a pair of parentheses,
  #   or (b) this could be the opening parenthesis in a function type.
  # The second LPAREN takes us again into the same state.
  # The RPAREN allows us to recognize that we have a function type of no parameters.
  # Hence, LPAREN RPAREN forms a direct_abstract_declarator.
  # At this point, the status of the first LPAREN is still undetermined (regular paren,
  # or beginning of a function type?) and so is the status of our direct_abstract_declarator
  # (does it form an abstract_declarator all by itself, or is it followed by LBRACK or LPAREN?).

  # In the general case, we have recognized either an abstract_declarator or
  # just a direct_abstract_declarator (which has spuriously reduced to abstract_declarator).
  # We may expect one the following:
  #   RPAREN (as shown above; closes an opening parenthesis after an abstract_declarator)
  #   LBRACK, LPAREN (continues a direct_abstract_declarator)
  # If we have recognized a direct_abstract_declarator, then either of these three
  # continuations is OK; if we have recognized an abstract_declarator that is not
  # a direct_abstract_declarator, then only RPAREN is OK.

In summary, we lack static context (we do not know whether we have read an
abstract_declarator or a direct_abstract_declarator) and because of that,
we do not know for sure which continuations we expect.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/30

In this production:

  direct_abstract_declarator:
  | ioption(direct_abstract_declarator) LBRACK type_qualifier_list? ioption(assignment_expression) RBRACK

changed ioption(direct_abstract_declarator) to option(direct_abstract_declarator).
This was done in reaction to two error situations that looked very similar to one
another. For some reason, this does not create a conflict. (I think it used to
create one? Or maybe I just missed this opportunity on 2015/09/28.)

612 states, 306 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/30

Added a phantom context parameter to [abstract_declarator]. This allows
distinguishing the two uses of abstract_declarator, namely within a type_name
and within a parameter_declaration. This provides more "static context" and
allows giving a better syntax error message, as this allows us to know what is
expected next: a closing parenthesis or a comma.

Strangely (?), this leads to fewer error states!

615 states, 302 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/09/30

Added a phantom context parameter to [specifier_qualifier_list_no_typedef_name].
This is consistent with the fact that [specifier_qualifier_list] already had one.
This gives me better static context in at least one state, and (strangely?) does
not increase the number of error states.

620 states, 302 error states.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2015/10/01

Introduced [other_identifier] as a more elegant way of recognizing a
[general_identifier] and calling [set_id_type].

